        \end{tabular}
    \end{center}
\end{table}
\end{enumerate}

\section{Postlab Questions}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Describe what happened to the pyrenoid bodies in Spirogyra spp. when
        you added Lugol’s Iodine Solution to them. Explain the importance of
        pyrenoid bodies to algal survival.

        The pyrenoid body is the main starch storage compartment within the
        Spirogyra. When Lugol's solution is added, the pyrenoid bodies are
        especially stained. Starch is the energy storage molecule for Spirogyra.
        Therefore it is necessary for its survival.

    \item Based on your observations of Spirogyra spp., what is the function of
        the conjugation tubes? Does this represent sexual or asexual reproduction?
        Justify your answer.

        The conjugation tube is a way of sexual reproduction for the Spirogyra.
        Using the conjugation tubes, the male cytoplasm migrates over and forms
        a zygote.

    \item Based on your observations, define Volvox spp. as a colonial organism.
        What does this suggest about the evolutionary event between unicellular
        algae and multicellular organisms?

        Volvox is a very fascinating organism. It is a colonial organism, where
        there are some specialization near the head of the colony. This may
        suggest that multicellular organisms first evolved from communities of
        single cell organisms.

    \item Based on your observations of organisms in today’s lab, explain how
        mold obtains nutrients even if they grow in dark, moist areas. Name the
        structure they use to obtain nutrients.

        Mold don't need to photosynthesis to get nutrients. In fact, they are
        parasitic. They get their nutrients by secreting enzymes onto the
        substrate and intaking the predigested nutrients.
    
    \item When you observed the mushroom section, you should have seen spores
        along the gills. What is the purpose of a basidiospore, and is it diploid
        (2n) or haploid (1n)?

        They are haploid cells, they are in fact gamates used to reproduce for
        the mushroom.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Conclusion}

For the most part the lab went well, except we by accident stained the Volvox
colony with Lugol's solution, which killed the colonies. But apart from that the
lab went well.

